e Jazz Singer debuted, there was no turning back.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 244, "name": "Significant sounds", "description": "The arrival of synchronised sound dramatically changed the movie business, allowing filmmakers to use sound in new and exciting ways which developed the use sound into own film language."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "creator_credit_for_label": "", "creator_credit_for_label_zh_hans": "", "creator_credit_for_label_pa": "", "creator_credit_for_label_hi": "", "headline_credit_for_label": "", "headline_credit_for_label_zh_hans": "", "headline_credit_for_label_pa": "", "headline_credit_for_label_hi": "", "title_for_label_zh_hans": "", "title_for_label_pa": "", "title_for_label_hi": "", "title_for_label_override_zh_hans": "", "title_for_label_override_pa": "", "title_for_label_override_hi": "", "description_for_label_zh_hans": "", "description_for_label_pa": "", "description_for_label_hi": "", "description_for_label_override_zh_hans": "", "description_for_label_override_pa": "", "description_for_label_override_hi": "", "description_zh_hans": "", "description_pa": "", "description_hi": "", "description_override_zh_hans": "", "description_override_pa": "", "description_override_hi": "", "title_for_label": "<p>Arrival of sound</p>", "description": "<p>It was a huge shift for Hollywood when synchronised sound arrived in the late 1920s. At first, actors, studios and journalists resisted the new technology, and some even called it the “Talkie Terror”. Though the first experiments began in the 1890s, it wasn’t until <i>Don Juan</i> in 1926 that a score and sound effects perfectly matched a movie, thanks to Warner Bros.’ Vitaphone system. <i>The Jazz Singer</i> (1927) went one step further, featuring not only synced music and sound effects but also the first recorded dialogue. Walt Disney was so impressed with the possibilities, he was inspired to create his own talking picture, <i>Steamboat Willie</i> (1928), which was not only one of the first cartoons with synchronised sound, it introduced the world to Mickey Mouse.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>It was a huge shift for Hollywood when synchronised sound arrived in the late 1920s. At first, actors, studios and journalists resisted the new technology, and some even called it the “Talkie Terror”. Though the first experiments began in the 1890s, it wasn’t until <i>Don Juan</i> in 1926 that a score and sound effects perfectly matched a movie, thanks to Warner Bros.’ Vitaphone system. <i>The Jazz Singer</i> (1927) went one step further, featuring not only synced music and sound effects but also the first recorded dialogue. Walt Disney was so impressed with the possibilities, he was inspired to create his own talking picture, <i>Steamboat Willie</i> (1928), which was not only one of the first cartoons with synchronised sound, it introduced the world to Mickey Mouse.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "<p>USA, c. 1894</p>", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial sections", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-05. Sound and Colour&nbsp;→ MI-05-AV02A", "The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ MI-05. Sound and Colour&nbsp;→ MI-05-C02"]}, {"label": "Object Types", "display_values": ["Moving image file/Digital"]}, {"label": "Materials", "display_values": ["Moving image file"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 22973}, "links": [], "creators_primary": [], "creators_other": [], "media_note": null, "holdings": [], "part_of": null, "parts": [], "part_siblings": [], "group": null, "group_works": [], "group_siblings": [], "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "181533", "eaas_environment_id": null, "production_places": [], "production_dates": [], "labels": [39416], "title_override_zh_hans": "", "title_override_pa": "", "title_override_hi": "", "credit_line_for_label_zh_hans": "", "credit_line_for_label_pa": "", "credit_line_for_label_hi": "", "credit_line_for_l